  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Developments\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970, US)\n- First international anti-money laundering guidelines\n- Initial focus on drug-related financial crimes\n\n2. Key Milestones\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) expanded reporting requirements\n\n3. Progressive Regulatory Approaches\n- Enhanced customer due diligence requirements\n- Mandatory transaction reporting\n- Stricter Know Your Customer (KYC) protocols\n- Increased cross-border information sharing\n\n4. Technological Adaptations\n- Regulations addressing cryptocurrency transactions\n- Digital asset reporting requirements\n- Enhanced digital forensic capabilities\n- Machine learning-based transaction monitoring\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- Expanding scope beyond traditional banking\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n- More comprehensive beneficial ownership regulations\n- Greater emphasis on preventing terrorist financing\n\n6. Global Coordination\n- Standardized international compliance frameworks\n- Multilateral information exchange mechanisms\n- Coordinated enforcement strategies\n\nThese developments reflect growing complexity in financial crimes and technological advancements.",
